    "url": "/en-uk/press-office/blogs-opeds/how-to-install-pagination-and-other-jekyll-plugins-with-a-gemfile-on-your-static-site/",
    "title": "How to install pagination and other Jekyll plugins with a Gemfile on your static site",
    "body": "2022/01/08 - Jekyll offers a lot of plugins for free that enable you to achieve a lot more than the standard Jekyll can. I had a hard time installing and using these plugins; however, perhaps that is because the official documentation on the Jekyll website isn‚Äôt clear enough for newbies like me. The plugin that I tried to install on my application is jekyll-paginate, which allows you to paginate your static blogs. I find this feature fascinating because it really helps simplying my static blog; otherwise, I really have no idea how you can efficiently manage a static site on which you‚Äôre going to publish a growing list of articles. In the Gemfile that you manually create in your application‚Äôs root directory, type in the following code: source 'https://rubygems. org'gem 'jekyll', '4. 2. 1'group :jekyll_plugins do	gem 'jekyll-paginate'endNote that the : at group :jekyll_plugins do is on the jekyll_plugins‚Äôs side. This is important. If you type group: jekyll_plugins do, you will likely get an error! Also it is a underscore mark instead of a hyphen in jekyll_plugins. After editing the Gemfile, you should also include in your _config. yml file the following code to intiate the plugins that you just installed: plugins:- jekyll-paginateNow you should open a command prompt and type in bundle install or simply bundle. After all these, you can now serve your site. BE CAREFUL!!! jekyll serve and bundle exec jekyll serve are not the same!!! This part wasted me hours to figure out. Since you installed the plugins with a Gemfile and bundle, you should always use bundle exec jekyll serv otherwise the plugin that you just installed won‚Äôt be effective in your app! "
