    "body": "2021/10/07 - The Biden Administration appears to be sticking with ex-President Trump‚Äôs ‚ÄúGet Tough on China‚Äù policy. Since the U. S. -China relations rapidly declined under Trump‚Äôs trade war with China, the United States has sanctioned dozens of Chinese entities including Beijing, Xinjiang, and Hong Kong SAR government officials, P. R. C. government administrative bureaus, private companies, and state-run organizations. While the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People‚Äôs Republic of China (MFA China) mentioned the possibility of establishing what it calls an ‚ÄúUnreliable Entities List‚Äù in response to U. S. sanctions, the Chinese government hasn‚Äôt made much visible progress on this pending regulation. It‚Äôs a good sign though that China passed the Anti-Sanctions Law in June 2021, but an Entity List, or even Entity Lists, is needed to secure China‚Äôs foreign policy and national security interests as well as the legally granted interests and rights of its private sector enterprises. While the U. S. frequently cites human rights and national security concerns when placing curbs on Chinese entities, the targets are mostly China‚Äôs national champions in technology. Taking into account the bills that the United States recently passed to designate the People‚Äôs Republic of China as a ‚Äústrategic competitor‚Äù and push for competition with the Asian civilization, U. S. sanctions are undermining the interests of China‚Äôs foreign policy, national security, and economy. They‚Äôre merely targeting rights abusers but the tools that the U. S. utilizes to surpress China‚Äôs growing power. China needs entity lists to target malign actors that seek to undermine its interests. This should include both domestic (e. g. Apple Daily) and foreign (e. g. H&amp;M) entities. This‚Äôs the most effective way to demonstrate China‚Äôs resolve to confront foreign aggression and its ability to retaliate against the United States and others. Imposing costs on entities that are engaged in, or represent the risk of becoming engaged in, destablizing activities is absolutely necessary to saftguard China‚Äôs interests. China should not worry about foreign companies‚Äô sentiment towards China. China must make it clear that friendly investors are more than welcomed, but malign actors are not welcomed on Chinese soil. We must always put national interests first. This is the redline that no one, not even the most generous investors, should be allowed to pass. "
